Republican strategy of resistance to re-election of Obama
Republican leaders justified their policies by the need to combat election fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth, arguing that cases of election fraud in the United States are rarer than deaths from lightning strikes.
In addition, Republican lawyers counted only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new trends will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
That’s why most state governments have passed laws since 2009 making it harder to register or vote.
This phenomenon gained a new dimension after the November 2010 election, which brought Republicans 675 new seats in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills restricting voting rights in 41 states were passed in 2011 alone.
The new election laws require voters to produce a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws shorten the period of early voting, abolish the right to register a voter on the day of expression of will and take away the right to vote from citizens with a criminal record.
Prior to the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to show a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to introduce such a requirement.
The U.S. Supreme Court confirmed in 2008 the constitutionality of the law passed in Indiana.
The Republican authorities rushed to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have initiated bills obliging voters to produce photo IDs in 34 states.
It is important to note that, unlike Quebec, American citizens do not have such a universal identity card as a health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of American citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have a photo ID issued by their state’s government agency.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a document.
At the same time, the cost of obtaining the required identity card often exceeds one hundred dollars.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African-Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over 65, and 20% of voters aged 18 to 29 do not have the required photo ID.
But that's not all.
Student voters who are believed to vote for Democratic candidates are not allowed to use a photo ID issued by their school in several states.
But these same states allow members of fishing and hunting clubs, who vote mainly for Republicans, to use the certificates issued by these clubs for voting.
Prior to 2004, no state required proof of U.S. citizenship to vote.
This is the first time such a requirement has been introduced in Arizona.
Since 2011, more than a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are obviously aimed at limiting the voting of immigrants from Latin America.
It is estimated that two-thirds of Latin American voters vote in favor of the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers initiated laws in 2011 abolishing voter registration on voting day in eight states.
They also restricted the right of individuals or groups to assist those wishing to register.
This restriction did not pass without consequences.
For example, during the 2004 elections, the voter registration campaign helped to put some 10 million citizens on the lists.
At the same time, measures taken since 2009 have led to a 17% drop in the registration rate of new voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers have passed laws in five other states aimed at reducing the early voting period.
During the 2008 Florida general election, 33% of voters who voted early were African-American, although the latter accounted for only 13% of the state's total voters.
The same thing happened with immigrants from Latin America.
Representing only 11% of voters, they made up 24% of citizens who voted ahead of schedule.
Unlike whites, who make up 76% of voters, only 46% of voters were early voters.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters are actively opposed to the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
Several draft laws were vetoed by Democratic governors.
The most controversial laws were suspended with the intervention of the Attorney General of the United States.
This allowed to partially limit the negative consequences.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring photo IDs.
However, the new rules that have come into effect will certainly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote in the 2012 elections.
Critics from Democrats condemn the bias of the laws that were passed, seeing them as an obvious focus on influencing the 2012 election results in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that states that passed these laws represent 171 of the 270 electoral college votes needed to win the presidential election.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes at the electoral level will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential election.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
Prostate cancer screening: test or not?
In fact, the PSA test gives sometimes erroneous results, false-negative and sometimes false-positive, which lead to useless medical intervention.
Men who are so reluctant to undergo medical examination, there is something to doubt even more.
To pass the test or not?
We asked for the opinion of two experts.
In studies conducted in the United States, there were numerous cases of infection among the groups studied, so the data obtained are difficult to interpret and it is difficult to develop any clear recommendations.
Another study, this time European, found different mortality rates in those patients who were screened and those who were not.
This study also showed, after a 12-year follow-up, that the likelihood of metastases is 30-40% higher in those who have not been screened.
Therefore, I would recommend taking the test starting at age 50, or 40 if one of the direct relatives had prostate cancer.
Men of African American descent are also at increased risk.
The key is to make the right decision once the cancer is detected.
Cancer can be both aggressive and sluggish.
The patient needs to explain the degree of risk of his cancer, offering him options, without mandatory treatment of prostate cancer, which does not pose a threat to life in the long term, and making a choice, in these cases, in favor of active surveillance of the disease.
To date, many men who have been diagnosed with cancer will not undergo treatment, since their cancer is not aggressive and does not pose a threat to life.
We will offer them active surveillance, and if the disease begins to progress, we will begin treatment.
Increasingly, we are accurately determining the criteria for deciding who should or should not undergo treatment.
I would recommend taking the test.
But it’s also important to consult your doctor to determine whether or not to take this test.
In collaboration with the International Association of Urology, Movembert has created a tool that allows you to evaluate all the pros and cons of passing the PSA test.
