Other officials responsible for road construction admitted that they received on the paw, inflating bills by 30-40% with fake additions.
Then one organizer from the mayor's party, Martin Dumont, accused Mr. Tremblay of deliberately turning a blind eye to the existence of a parallel budget that filled the party's cash desks with dirty money.
Following these revelations, Mr. Tremblay resigned in early November, plunging Montreal into a deep crisis.
Chantal Rulo was one of the first MPs in Montreal to sound the alarm.
The mayor of the Riviera de Prairie district in the east of the island, she has been resisting since 2010 the sale of a municipal site bought for $ 5 million and resold for $ 1.6 million to developers in the midst of a construction boom.
70% of dirty money in election campaigns
She says that in the investigation, which will eventually be launched, she “will pull a thread that allows you to understand the functioning of the system infested with ants to stop gangrene and identify those responsible.”
This process is characterized as “painful, but positive”.
We are in the process of cleaning up the wound, but Montreal will need its own investigative team and observer to avoid the return of questionable practices.
How we clean up at home.
Regularly.
Jacques Duchenault, for his part, notes that “officials stole hundreds of millions of dollars,” but he is particularly concerned about the role of “elective officials who knew about this scheme,” but did not participate in the fraud.
Given that the share of dirty money in the financing of the election campaign in Quebec reaches 70%, he jokes: “I was told that it was only a pale reflection of reality.”
The government of Quebec proposes to limit donations to parties to $ 100, but, according to him, this will not change the situation: “Until we strictly limit election spending, there will be dirty money in politics.”
It requires a complete overhaul of the system of granting government contracts and financing parties: “We can not go lower; boldly understanding the essence of things, we will be able to build a house on a stronger foundation, with better control and legality.”
If this story casts a shadow on the international image of Quebec and Montreal, Mr. Duchenault calls on those who laugh to look into their own courtyard ...
