Poland and Space.
Last week, at a meeting of European Space Agency ministers, Poland was accepted by the twentieth member of the European Space Agency as the second country from the countries of the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on September 12, 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and has been actively involved in a number of the agency's projects over the years.
But the path to space Poland began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish enthusiasts were engaged in flights into space, but this was not always met with understanding.
Let me recall, for example, the lecture by A. Sternfeld, who on December 6, 1933, presented at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory ideas from his pioneering work "Introduction to Astronautics".
The ideas of the young engineer (1905) left the audience indifferent, after several years Sternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomsky was interested in his work.
In 1934, in France, Sternfeld won the Robert Esno-Peltrie and André Louis Hirsch Award for "Introduction to Astronautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomsky (1899-1966), mentioned above, later became a great promoter of astronomy and astronautics.
He has published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and has written a number of books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomsky became a well-known world advocate of astronautics, and his contribution was appreciated by the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the moon was named in his honor.
Already in 1925 in Poland, a railway ladder was built, equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of this idea remained unknown, as well as the details of the project.
It is not even clear whether the rocket was used to accelerate or to brake the trolley.
Information about this ladder is known only from the press of that era.
Since 1933, the Polish artillery began to think about missile arrows.
The research was carried out by the Armament Engineering Section in collaboration with professors Mechislav Wolfke and Gustav Mokzytski.
From the surviving materials, it can be seen that the research has reached the stage of practical tests.
But with the arrival of German troops, work was interrupted.
In 1937, the idea of a photoelectric fighter rocket, proposed by the engineer Rogozinsky, appeared in a specialized press, and the following year the work “Air Torpedo Rocket and Aviation Bomb Rocket” by the author of Lelyva-Kzhivoblotsky appeared.
Both projects were designed for the military use of rocket engines.
Before the war, all projects of military use of missile equipment was handled by the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated all the work.
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of activity, the work ended due to the outbreak of the war.
The next scientific work devoted to astronautics appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Society for Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time about society mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the magazine "Problems", which publishes four voluminous articles on astronautics.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotovich proposed to organize a society that will be engaged in astronautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects were already gaining momentum, and it was clear that space research was a promising industry.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Society of Astronautics (POA) tried to join the International Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951), and in the autumn of POA became its full member.
The following year, Kazimierz Zarankevich, the first chairman of the International Astronautical Federation (1902-1959), became deputy chairman of the International Astronautical Federation.
He remained in this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PAA has made a significant contribution to the development of the highly successful RM weather rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which was the first Polish rocket to perform scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957, and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The missile, capable of covering a distance of 1,800 m, was about 80 cm long, and its weight was less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959, a two-stage RM-2 missile was tested at the Bledovsky wasteland.
This missile was about 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the rocket was already able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 missile could overcome 14.5 km, and its task was to observe high-altitude wind.
But in 1962, further development was suspended.
The successor to the first missiles of the RM type was the Meteor-1 missile, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The missile was conceived as a two-stage, its total length was 510 cm, and the initial weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (designated Meteor-1A, -1B, and -1C) were developed, which varied in camera size for scientific equipment.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space volume of 0.4 liters, the Meteor-1B - 0.34 liters, and the Meteor-1C - 0.62 liters.
The maximum range of all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Aviation Institute developed the Meteor-2 rocket, and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket with a launch weight of 380 kg was able to bring a payload weighing 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
Then, versions of Meteor-2N and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also worth mentioning the accession of Poland to COSPAR (Committee on Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of the COSPAR National Committee two years later.
In addition, within the framework of the Intercosmos program, Poland participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978, the Polish pilot Miroslav Germashevsky became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
Repeal of the Public Works Act is not the solution.
Last week, the constitutional court annulled the law on public works.
The ruling sparked a lively debate in society.
It will certainly be interesting to look at this issue from a broader perspective.
Liberally oriented economies in the EU, as well as in the globalized world, are based on the principle of multiple, unregulated economic competition.
In essence, this means that individual economic units, national economic systems, are in constant conflict with each other.
This is due to the principle of free trade and free, unrestricted movement of private capital, together with unbridled financial speculation.
As a result of a significant difference in the cost of labor (wages), price stress arises.
Under this concept, it is necessary to understand the state when the manufacturer, through the delivery of a cheap product, tries to withstand economic competition by “shipping down” the value of a competitor in order to take a large part of the market and, thus, increase his own income.
On a mass scale, this means for most entrepreneurs either the transfer of production abroad, or cheap purchases abroad, or disappearance. As a result, unemployment increases in those countries where the cost of labor, compared to others, is high.
Since private capital does not bear any social responsibility, including for unemployment, the inevitable expenditure of the state on social needs increases.
In general, the situation increases the reluctance of entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thereby compensate for the social economic and social damage they cause in the pursuit of profit.
The situation is so well known that it is not necessary to provide specific statistics.
Unceremonious methods of private capital create a situation at the level of the economies of individual states when the governments of countries are forced to compete with each other in order to artificially reduce the social level of their population in order to attract foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments are handing over their own populations to private capital despite social decline.
This is reflected primarily in the changes in the current legislation.
The aim is to force their people economically to submit to the dictates of private capital, especially in the field of wages.
This acts as a system of economic coercion in the case of long-term unemployment and at the same time serves as a tool for reducing the rights of workers in the field of labor legislation.
As a result, the level of poverty increases, and at the same time the difference between the poor and the rich.
In Germany, for several years, there has been a public distribution of products to the poor, who are unable to feed themselves with their own labor.
The number of these people is already approaching a million.
As part of improving the competitiveness of the German economy, there are cases when employed people receive such a salary that the state must pay them extra to get a living wage.
Such a scandal became known to the public in the case of additional employees of the Bundestag.
Economic measures in almost all southern EU states undoubtedly lead to the same state in which people under the pressure of a catastrophic fall in social status are forced to either emigrate, as it was in the 19th century, or exist on a poverty-stricken salary in the margins of society in the hope that private investment capital will someday come to the country.
But I wonder where he will come from?
If capital comes from other EU countries, then poverty will move from one country to another, or it will not come at all, since the Chinese, the Hindu, the Brazilian, the Turks, the Moroccan, the Egyptian, the African is still working for a share of European wages.
This applies to all of Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media are sickeningly claiming that the state cannot participate in the capital of its own economy, that a managed economy leads to economic disaster.
Private capital insists that the state should not interfere in the economy.
Next, we should answer the question whether private capital, now practically managing politics and the whole state, does not act for its own selfish purposes?
The definite answer is yes.
Proof is the existence of almost omnipotent and omnipresent lobbies in all states.
As a result, we have a hopeless situation, manifested in corruption, ensuring mutual benefits, in legislation where almost everything deserves punishment, but is not a crime.
In Germany, the situation is such that government ministries, due to lack of financial resources, entrust the development of draft laws to private law firms that are closely related to industry.
Then these bills are approved by the Bundestag.
All power comes not from the people, as the constitution of the Western type states, but from financially powerful groups that prefer their own interests.
It is obvious that liberal-oriented democracy is now quickly in such a situation, as described by Appian in the work “The Crisis of the Roman Empire in the Days of Caesar and Pompey”: “The state has long been falling apart, and departments are engaged in violence.
Bribery, illegal obtaining of favors with the help of stones and swords.
Bribery and corruption flourished without any bans, and people went to the polls with a pre-sold voice"... decent people did not run for the post of ruler at all, in the end, one day the state was left without a consul for eight months."... "Seriously began to say that the only salvation in this terrible situation is autocracy and the need to choose an energetic person."
As in ancient times, in modern society, their own reckless interests prevail without taking into account public interests.
Private capital is no longer inherently intended for public use.
The current result is no different from the past: an unprecedented decline of the elite without any effort to carry out reforms of a deeper nature.
Hence, the reason for the emergence of fascist and communist regimes, we must look for in the reckless liberalization of economic systems of the 19th and 20th centuries.
To date, the absence of these regimes and the existence of a liberal-type democracy can be perceived as a certain pause, after which the next round is expected.
First of all, it is tragic that the current elite completely ignores the consequences of hundreds of thousands of victims in the future, the humanitarian and social disasters that we are already witnessing, along with crimes against humanity, as we know from old and new history.
Repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution, or at least not forever.
Under the pressure of competition at both international and national and European levels, the Government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for ways to further reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is therefore systemic.
The solution is targeted political and social reforms that will strengthen the share of the state in the economy, strengthen the role of citizens in the management of the state and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society in favor of the state.
