MVRDV architects prove that real adventures are not only in the imagination - on the example of Speikenisse and his newly built Book Mountain - 2 photos
“This building seems fun to me, it looks futuristic, at last we can see something interesting again,” says Lisette Verhaig, passing by on the edge of the road.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT specialist at a nearby large enterprise, thinks, "No, this building is really beautiful."
But I ask myself, why do we need another library today?
Everyone has the Internet, iPad, and e-books.
Now no one voluntarily goes to such old-fashioned libraries, right?
Speikenisse, a little-noted sleeping town near Rotterdam, holds an unusual record.
Its population of 80,000 has the lowest level of education in the Netherlands.
To combat this unfortunate circumstance, a few years ago it was decided to contribute to general education and build seven fictional bridges, which are depicted on euro banknotes, in the form of picturesquely painted miniatures of reinforced concrete.
The success of this educational initiative was modest.
And then the fathers of the city realized that they had the only opportunity to overcome the statistics: to build a library here!
Vinnie Maas of MVRDV, a Rotterdam-based architectural bureau, master of bold column charts and author of witty, sometimes even cynical, buildings, approached the task with his usual equanimity and appeared at a competitive audition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a grin on his face.
And while the jury members puzzledly looked around and shrugged their shoulders, the daring Maas folded a pyramid in size from his original gift and ended the speech in defense of his project with the following words: “Dear citizens!”
Here it is, my proposal: "Book Mountain" in Speikenisse, the so-called Bookenberg!
Nine years later, this mountain, worth 30 million euros, has grown.
It is part of the revitalization project, which also includes an underground garage, supermarket, post office and several adjacent residential buildings and townhouses for a total of 50 apartments.
In early November, Book Mountain was awarded the second prize of the contest “Best Library of the Netherlands 2012”.
Also, the project participates in the national Dutch competition of wooden structures in 2012.
Thus, the faceless suburb, which previously could not offer anything but a postmodern pedestrian zone and a surprisingly ugly town hall, the white facades of which suggest the idea of a dairy plant, became richer in one modern piece of architecture.
But most importantly - in Speikenissa appeared the first public building of cultural purpose in the history of this town.
The long road to the book
First impression: book Eldorado under the cap for cheese.
There is only one elevator passing in the center of the mountain range, because real fans of architecture and reading will prefer to explore this area on foot.
Glazed from all sides, the room is bright and easily visible, floors made of burnt brick and elegant street lights unmistakably create a feeling of a public city square.
The urban environment is recreated perfectly.
The look is involuntarily looking for benches, dogs and football-playing boys and girls.
And everywhere - books, books, books.
“Typically, bookshelves stand along the facades, and in the middle is a large dark hall, usually uncomfortable and faceless,” says Vini Maas.
We put the classic configuration of space on its head and pulled the reading area from the inside out.
The inner space of the book mountain is used skillfully: in the center there are offices, an Internet library, a chess club, an environmental center and technical premises.
Particularly pleased with the black bookshelves, which serve as either wall decoration, parapets, or stair railings.
Their appearance, texture and smell are unusual.
Even sophisticated architects and construction engineers are lost in guessing what this unknown material is.
“We wanted to work with secondary materials,” explains Jop Trauborst, project manager representing the Speikenisse community, in accordance with the requirements of the standard.
And once at an agricultural enterprise in Friesland, we met a suitable by-product of agriculture.
For many years in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands, an artificial fibrous material of millimeter thickness has been used as a lining under the roots.
It is cheap and saves time.
Thin textiles serve one or two seasons, after which it can be thrown away.
For the library, this canvas - for the first time in such volumes - was pressed in a panel four centimeters thick.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the so-called landbauplastic (KLP) turns into a dark, uniform, durable material, smelling a little like a new car and a little sneaker.
There are 105 steps to the top.
Those who overcome the path of almost 500 meters will be rewarded in a literary cafe not only with a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and wood ficus in pots.
They care about the atmosphere, and first of all about the correct humidity on the literary mountain.
Costs of a new soul
“It’s hard to believe, but this building, despite its many glass surfaces, is a model project in terms of ecology,” says Trowborst.
The heat of the earth is used for its heating and cooling.
Although the Book Mountain is under a glass cap, even on clear days the sun gets inside only for a short time.
Wide glued wood farms, arranged perpendicular to the glass facade, give shade and take on most of the sun's rays.
The climate in the room is very pleasant.
The rest of the protection is provided by fully automatic roller blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the IT skeptic mentioned above, has already visited the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was here, too.
As well as the teacher of traditional Chinese medicine Cynthia Bogard, who called Bookenberg “the soul of Speikenisse, which has long been lacking.”
The reason: a few weeks before the opening, each resident received an invitation to donate one book from his own collection.
These books were supposed to take up empty space on the shelves of the not yet fully staffed library - at that time there were 70,000 books in it.
The idea worked.
The shelves are stacked up.
“There’s nothing worse than a half-empty library,” says architect Viny Maas.
“I think that thanks to our invitation, now every resident is somehow connected to this new house.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it's just for decoration.
Thus, MVRDV managed to solve the royal task, which in professional jargon is called identity creation.
Speikenisse wrote his literary history.
Let them be young and uneducated.
This is only the starting point for building an identity.
Szabo: “Germans should play a bigger role”
Germany abstained in the vote to recognize Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on relations between the United States and Europe, in doing so, Berlin is balancing on a narrow diplomatic path.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany first made it clear that it would vote against the Palestinian application for observer status at the United Nations.
Berlin abstained in the vote.
Why not?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support Israeli actions in Gaza.
Germany now needs to be careful about its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I believe that she does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained in a vote to impose a no-fly zone.
In the end, NATO made this proposal.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yes, it is.
The fact is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, namely, moving from the policy, which, so to speak, was ruled by the United States, to the German foreign policy itself.
In addition, the situation is complicated by the fact that the Europeans do not have a coherent common policy.
Thus, the Germans again find themselves between the two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe that so far they are only groping for their role, but are on the way to a “more normal” foreign policy.
Such a foreign policy, which is carried out by France or Great Britain.
What exactly does “normal” foreign policy mean from the German point of view?
This is a willingness to take a position in their national interests that is independent of the position of the United States or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policy, that is, on exports and ties with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany’s economic interests are very different from those of other major states, and therefore Germany must defend its interests.
Did these economic interests influence the position in the Middle East conflict and the vote in the UN?
First, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, in particular in the Gulf States.
Therefore, it needs to be careful not to offend the public and elites in Arab countries.
Either way, it plays a role.
But I wouldn't attach too much importance to it, it's not a completely one-sided relationship.
But in any case, this plays an important role in the calculations of the Germans.
Has Germany harmed its relationship with the United States by abstaining from making important decisions, such as voting on Palestine?
I am sure that understanding of the German position prevails in Europe and even in the United States.
So I don’t think it was as dramatic as the Libyan issue.
Perhaps Germany will even gain some respect in this way.
After all, this signals that it should be taken seriously as a player in the international arena and that its interests should be taken into account.
There are different views in Europe about the Palestinian initiative.
The U.S., on the other hand, has been clear in its support for the veto.
Is there a difference of opinion between the United States and many European countries?
Because of American domestic politics, such differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama government has a deep understanding of the European position.
But due to the local political situation, the government, of course, cannot openly take such a position.
I believe that significant differences of opinion are not as significant as they always seem to be.
If you consider the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is not at all enthusiastic about Netanyahu’s policies.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close ties with Israel and the United States on the one hand and its position as an essential partner in the EU on the other?
I think that’s what makes the situation so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a bit easier for the Germans if there was a single, consistent European policy, but now this is not the case.
Therefore, they cannot take a broader approach and are instead forced to act on their own view of the situation.
That’s what they do with the euro.
I think that in the future Germany will take a leading role in the development of a common European position.
It is clear that this is not easy for Germany, at least because of its ties with Israel.
This subject has always been sensitive.
But I think it’s clear to the Germans that they need to play a more independent role.
If Germany sees itself as an important international player, will it really take on the leading role?
Or is Germany still in the lead?
Germany is not yet used to this, it is still always unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is still always difficult to play a significant role.
Consider, for example, the euro crisis - every time Germany takes on an important role, a variety of anti-German feelings are manifested.
The Germans don’t just deal with it.
Actually, it's an old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
It should take into account a variety of neighbors and opinions, and this is not easy.
So, the US influence in European politics is constantly weakening, but at the moment the EU is not filling this vacuum, who then remains?
The Germans will just have to play a bigger role.
Even if you do not like it, unpleasant or increases dislike for you - this is life!
Stephen Sabo is the deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institution where academics and political scientists from Europe and North America work together to explore the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Sabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, U.S. foreign policy, and transatlantic relations.
Trademark protection in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani is a world-famous brand, Polo Ralph Lauren is also.
What is Armani Polo?
This is a completely officially registered name in China, which has nothing to do with the companies from whose names it is formed.
However, it will be protected until the owners of the original names file a claim.
But even then, it is unclear whether they will be able to defend their rights.
“Foreigners are finding it increasingly difficult to protect their trademarks in China,” says Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing, a company specializing in trademark infringement in the Far East.
On my desk every week appears on a new case of this kind.
Imitators only need to add a couple of letters to get the right to register their trademarks.
So from Gucci you get Lu-Gucci, instead of Prada you can register Prada-Kny.
In the same way, German enterprises, for example, the manufacturer of sports goods Puma, are legally copied.
Pattloch opens a folder with records of the trademark office in Beijing.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company registered there the trademark Zegna DF Puma, an artificial name that also uses the name of the Ermenegildo Zegna fashion house.
The fact that the Chinese are world champions in copying and violating intellectual property rights is known.
In large cities, there are multi-storey department stores selling almost exclusively fakes.
However, the cases of Pattloch are not like that. On behalf of his clients, he opposes the fact that Chinese enterprises officially receive from the trademark registration office the right to use the name, which is already protected somewhere else.
The Chinese call it Ban Minpai, the passenger brand.
This word is associated with "ban daquan".
This is the name of women who hunt for rich men.
The Chinese authorities do not admit guilt.
“It hurts the business, it needs to be fought,” Pattloch said.
