Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the most important sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia and tripper (gonorrhea).
Common viral STIs are HIV, human papillomavirus, genital herpes, and hepatitis.
Pubic pediculosis and scabies are parasitic STIs.
What are the main affected groups?
Syphilis and gonorrhea occur mainly in men who have sex with men.
Robert Koch Institute believes that at least four out of every five cases of syphilis registered in Germany, the transmission occurs as a result of sexual contact between men.
In heterosexual adults, sexually transmitted diseases are chlamydial infections, trichomoniasis, candidiasis (fungus), gonorrhea and human papillomavirus.
HIV prevalence among heterosexual adults is relatively low, but about 20 percent of new HIV infections occur in this group.
Chlamydial infections are significantly more common among young people than among other population groups.
According to European data, three-quarters of all infections affect young people between the ages of 15 and 25.
Human papillomavirus is also common among young people.
How does the number of infections change?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are registered.
The incidence of syphilis, according to the Robert Koch Institute, more than doubled from 1,697 cases in 2001 to 3,698 cases in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has been declining since 2007.
In 2011, there were about 2,700 cases.
This is about one-tenth less than the previous year.
What symptoms indicate a venereal disease?
In infectious diseases, ulcers can occur in the genital area, complaints when urinating, discharge, pain in the lower abdomen, as well as bubbles or seals.
However, they are often not accompanied by pain and other symptoms and go unnoticed.
How can I protect myself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but do not give one hundred percent protection.
After all, part of the causative agents of sexually transmitted diseases can also be spread by contact infection and through close physical contact.
Therefore, experts recommend regular examination, especially with frequent changes in sexual partners.
With early diagnosis, you can cure most STIs and avoid long-term consequences.
