Every week, students explore apocalyptic phenomena such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
This semester, when religion professor Stuart Sharma decided to teach a course about the end of the world, he knew he had irresistible bait: the end of the “long countdown” of the Mayan calendar, December 21, which many people grasped as proof that the end of the world was coming.
But Sharma had no idea what was coming in the next couple of months: the catastrophic Hurricane Sandy, the financial crisis that some have called “long-armageddon,” and the growing conflict that is dragging Israel into, a place where Christian doomsday theorists believe the Apocalypse will begin.
“I didn’t realize it was going to be the most apocalyptic semester of all,” Sharma told Rutgers-Camden University students this week.
